definition.value: A infectious disease caused by a virus of the genus Lentivirus.

Human immunodeficiency virus. A non-taxonomic and historical term referring to any of two species, specifically HIV-1 and/or HIV-2. Prior to 1986, this was called human T-lymphotropic virus type III/lymphadenopathy-associated virus (HTLV-III/LAV). From 1986-1990, it was an official species called HIV. Since 1991, HIV was no longer considered an official species name; the two species were designated HIV-1 and HIV-2.
Infection where the agent is a retrovirus.
Infection where the agent is a lentivirus.

Infection where HIV is the agent; includes the spectrum of human immunodeficiency virus infections that range from asymptomatic seropositivity, thru AIDS-related complex (ARC), to acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS).
A syndrome with primarily psychiatric signs and/or symptoms.
A syndrome in which the underlying genetic cause is known.
Any of various syndromes primarily affecting the immunological system of the body.
Syndromes primarily affecting the immunological system.
Syndromes in which there is a deficiency or defect in the mechanisms of immunity, either cellular or humoral.

A syndrome resulting from the acquired deficiency of cellular immunity caused by the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV). It is characterized by the reduction of the Helper T-lymphocytes in the peripheral blood and the lymph nodes. Symptoms include generalized lymphadenopathy, fever, weight loss, and chronic diarrhea. Patients with AIDS are especially susceptible to opportunistic infections (usually pneumocystis carinii pneumonia, cytomegalovirus (CMV) infections, tuberculosis, candida infections, and cryptococcosis), and the development of malignant neoplasms (usually non-Hodgkin's lymphoma and Kaposi's sarcoma). The human immunodeficiency virus is transmitted through sexual contact, sharing of contaminated needles, or transfusion of contaminated blood.

An acquired defect of cellular immunity associated with infection by the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV), a CD4-positive T-lymphocyte count under 200 cells/microliter or less than 14% of total lymphocytes, and increased susceptibility to opportunistic infections and malignant neoplasms. Clinical manifestations also include emaciation (wasting) and dementia. These elements reflect criteria for AIDS as defined by the CDC in 1993.
Infection where the agent is the HIV-1 virus.
Infection where the agent is the HIV-2 virus.
An HIV infection which is symptomatic in nature.
Diseases transmitted or propagated by sexual conduct.
Viral diseases transmitted or propagated by sexual conduct.
Bacterial diseases transmitted or propagated by sexual conduct.
An infection in which transmission is facilitated via sexual contact.
Bacterial infections organized by the primary area of infection.
Bacterial infections primarily affecting the genitourinary system.
Bacterial infections primarily affecting the genitalia.
Bacterial infections primarily affecting the urinary tract.
Infections with bacteria of the order Spirochaetales.
A disease caused by a spirochetal infection.
A disease caused by a treponemal infection.
Syphilis acquired non-congenitally, usually through sexually transmitted infection.
Syphilis beyond the tertiary stage; syphilis which had entered the stage of fulminant anergic necrotic encephalitis.
Neurosyphilis of the late quaternary stage.
A stage of syphilis that occurs fifteen to thirty years after the initial infection; it can include gumma formation and cardiovascular or central nervous system involvement (neurosyphilis).

Infection of the brain or spinal cord by Treponema pallidum. It occurs many years following the original infection which remained untreated. Signs and symptoms include abnormal gait, blindness, depression, paralysis, seizures and dementia.

A severe neuropsychiatric disorder, classified as an organic mental disorder and caused by the chronic meningoencephalitis that leads to cerebral atrophy in late-stage syphilis. Degenerative changes are associated primarily with the frontal and temporal lobar cortex. The disease affects approximately 7% of infected individuals.
A disease by infectious agent that results in infection, has material basis in Gram-negative bacteria.
A disease by infectious agent that results in infection, has material basis in Gram-positive bacteria.
A infectious disease caused by a virus of the family Herpesviridae.
Infection where the agent is a herpesvirus.
A infectious disease caused by a virus of the subfamily Alphaherpesvirinae.
A disease caused by the herpes simplex virus.

Herpes simplex virus 1 and 2 (HSV-1 and HSV-2), also known by their taxonomical names Human alphaherpesvirus 1 and Human alphaherpesvirus 2, are two members of the human Herpesviridae family, a set of viruses that produce viral infections in the majority of humans.
A disease caused by a chlamydial infection.
A calculation from zero or more input values (called operands) to an output value.
A calculation that combines two elements (called operands) to produce another element. More formally, a binary operation is an operation of arity two.
The quality of being unlike or dissimilar.
A measure of difference between the observed value of a variable and some other value, often that variable's mean.
A deviation from a rule or from what is regarded as normal; an outlier.
Abnormalities of one's body either congenital or acquired.
A physical anomaly present at birth.
The alteration of a morphological feature.
An abnormal formation, especially an abnormal developmental feature.
Any malformation or condition related to malformation which is present at birth, regardless of cause.
Any malformation that is a part of or affects the urogenital system.
Malformations of the genital system (genitals, gonads, etc.) or any of its constituent parts.
